Available Customizations

Headings:

Use # for level-1 headings (largest), ## for level-2, ### for level-3, etc.
Example: # Big Title vs. ### Smaller Subtitle.
This is the primary way to vary text size perception.


Bold and Italic:

Bold: **text** or __text__ (e.g., Mark Wallier).
Italic: *text* or _text_ (e.g., portfolio).
Combine: **_bold and italic_** (e.g., highlight).


Hyperlinks:

[Text](URL) (e.g., [GitHub](https://github.com) or [Email](mailto:mark.e.wallier@gmail.com)).
Useful for contact info or project links.


Code Blocks:

Inline: `code` (e.g., python preprocess.py).
Block: ```python
pythonprint("Hello, GitHub!")


Lists:

Unordered: - item or * item (e.g., - Feature 1).
Ordered: 1. item (e.g., 1. Step one).
Nested: Add two spaces before - or 1. for sub-items.


Tables:

Use  to create columns, with - for headers:
markdown| Feature       | Status  |
|---------------|---------|
| Data Cleaning | Done    |
| Visualization | In Progress |
Renders as:


FeatureStatusData CleaningDoneVisualizationIn Progress


Images:

![Alt Text](URL) (e.g., ![Demo](demo/screenshot.png)).
Upload images to your repo (e.g., in a demo/ folder) and link them.


Badges:

Add dynamic badges like build status or license:
markdown[![License](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-blue.svg)](LICENSE)
(You’d need to host the badge image URL—check shields.io for options.)


Quotes:

Use > for a blockquote:
text> This is a cool project!
Renders as:

This is a cool project!


Task Lists:

- [ ] Todo or - [x] Done (e.g., - [ ] Add features, - [x] Write README).
Useful for tracking progress.


Limitations

Font Size/Style: GitHub’s Markdown doesn’t support custom font sizes (e.g., <h1> tags won’t work as HTML is restricted). Headings are your best bet for size variation.
Colors: No direct color control—use bold/italics or emojis (e.g., :rocket:) for emphasis.
Advanced Styling: HTML is limited; avoid <font> or <style> tags—they won’t render.
